poem:
Chartlewhim

Under lampglow, creasy charts
went flutter-furl across the floor;
The graticule with gridwise hearts
sang merithreads galore.

The mapwright murmured, “Mind your care—
the Wayward Wyrm-of-Where will twist;
The Crosshatch Gnat nests in the air;
the Drift will fog your wrist.

Trust not the sly Compassnag—
it wheedles north to wobble south;
The Siren-Scale will brag and brag
and salt your journey’s mouth.

He took his brave waywiser then,
the span-pronged measure keen and neat;
He kissed the rose-of-north, and when
it whirred, he loosed his feet.

By loxodromic lanes he strode,
past dentifjords and buckle-sands;
Through contour-choirs the paper flowed
and hissed beneath his hands.

Upon a merithread he paused;
the Misdirrex slid out of shade—
all loop and snare, with tangles gauzed,
its legend-ink afraid.

Its latitude tongue lapped longitude;
its rhumb-lines reeled and writhed;
It wheezed “Here-be” with attitude,
and every route was scythed.

Clack sang the neatline; snap the scale;
he sprang with span and silver rule;
Three arcs he drew, a trisserail,
and pricked its tangle-spool.

He pinned it to a polar pip,
a clean meridian, north to heel;
The Misdirrex gave one last slip
beneath the compass wheel.

He bore the rumor home again
to Mapwright in the midnight glow;
“O legendbright! Tra-loo! Amen!”
cried inks in indigo.

Under lampglow, creasy charts
lay smooth as moons along the floor;
The graticule with gridwise hearts
dreamed merithreads galore.
